#X text 49 28 We'll actually get back to this \, but it's nice to introduce this idea right here. Of course we have a basic usage of a keyboard MIDI input to control the pitch \, but we might want to control other things on the patch depending on the note input region. A classic example is controlling the cutoff of a filter., f 69;
#X text 175 312 reference;
#X text 286 268 We need ti have a reference point and we have a track amount which means how much of the pitch difference is used to control something. In this example we're doing something funny \, which is changing the tracking amount to cnotrol the pitch itself \, so we're distorting it., f 37;
#X text 188 417 With the difference in semiton we convert it to cents by multiplying to 100 \, but this can also be considered the tracking amount percentage. Then we convert to ratio and use it as an interval on the reference point., f 47;
